body:
Ops, I accidentally inverted the position of type in function declaration and I get a compiler internal error.

```
fn inc_vec(&mut v: Vec<u8>) {// error of type position
fn inc_vec(v: &mut Vec<u8>) {// correct syntax
```

I'm not sure if this error was just reported here.
I tried this code:

```
fn main() {
    groups(5)
}

fn groups(n: usize) {
    let mut v: Vec<u8> = vec![0; n];

    for w in 1..256 {
        inc_vec(&mut v);
        println!("{} {} {} {} {} -- {}", v[0], v[1], v[2], v[3], v[4], w);
    }
}

fn inc_vec(&mut v: Vec<u8>) {// error of type position
    let mut carry = false;
    let n = v.len();

    if v[n-1] == (n-2) as u8 {
        v[n-1] = 0;
        carry = true;
    } else {
        v[n-1] += 1;
    }
    let mut i = n-2;
    while carry {
        if v[i] == (n-2) as u8 {
            v[i] = 0;
            i -= 1;
        } else {
            v[i] += 1;
            carry = false;
        }
    }
}
```

I expected to see this happen: <explanation>

